1. Graph Engine
MF-1: UpdateNode ignores merge strategy — reducer integration is a TODO — HIGH

node.rs:128: // TODO: Apply merge strategy and per-field reducers. The UpdateNode clones state, calls merge() (which is a no-op on PlainState), and ignores MergeStrategy::Replace, MergeStrategy::Merge, and the entire Reducer<T> system in reducer/mod.rs. This means the reducer module (Overwrite, Append, Sum, MergeMap) is dead code — it's never wired into execution.

MF-2: merge_state is unimplemented!() in runtime — HIGH

runtime/mod.rs:61: unimplemented!("merge_state is generated by macro for each State type"). The macro doesn't exist. Any code path that calls this panics at runtime.

MF-3: No subgraph execution in StateGraph — MEDIUM

The state_graph module (LangGraph-style API) has no concept of nesting a StateGraph inside another. The agent/mod.rs has subgraph support via YAML config, but the typed StateGraph<S> builder has no add_subgraph() method. Users building graphs programmatically can't compose them.

MF-4: No graph export/serialization — MEDIUM

The StateGraph and Graph structs can't be serialized to DOT, JSON, or Mermaid format for documentation or visualization. The visualization.rs generates ASCII art only. The graph_visualizer.rs generates a StateGraphVisualization struct but no standard export format (DOT/Mermaid).

MF-5: ParallelExecutor has no public execute method — MEDIUM

ParallelExecutor has collect_results and merge_results but they are #[allow(dead_code)] private methods. There's no public API to actually run parallel branches — users can't use it. It's infrastructure that's never wired up.

MF-6: Placeholder node functions in runtime — LOW

runtime/mod.rs:194: Nodes are registered with placeholder_fn (identity function) that gets replaced later via register_node. If a node handler is never registered, it silently passes through instead of erroring.

2. State Management
MF-7: No persistent state across runs — HIGH

InMemoryCheckpointer loses all data when the process exits. There is no file-based or database-backed Checkpointer implementation. The Checkpointer trait is well-designed for this, but no durable implementation exists.

MF-8: No scoped/namespaced state per node — LOW

Every node reads/writes the same flat SharedState. There's no isolation — Node A can clobber Node B's keys. LangGraph has "channels" for this. No equivalent here.

3. LLM Clients
MF-9: No retry/backoff on LLM API calls — HIGH

The HttpLLMClient does a single HTTP request with no retry. If OpenAI returns 429 (rate limit) or 503, the call fails immediately. The MCP module has RetryMCPClient with exponential backoff + circuit breaker — nothing equivalent exists for LLM calls.

MF-10: No token counting before sending — MEDIUM

There's no way to estimate token count before sending a request. Users can't implement context window management (truncating history to fit the model's limit). No tiktoken/tokenizer integration.

MF-11: No cost tracking — LOW

TokenUsage tracks counts but has no pricing data. Users can't get dollar costs per run. Would need a pricing table per model.

MF-12: Anthropic adapter doesn't support tool calling — MEDIUM

AnthropicAdapter has no build_payload_with_tools or parse_tool_calls override. Anthropic's tool use API is different from OpenAI's (uses tool_use content blocks). Tool calling with Claude silently falls back to chat() ignoring tools.

MF-13: HuggingFace chat_stream is fake streaming — LOW

huggingface.rs:353: "Small delay to simulate streaming" — it buffers the full response then sends word-by-word with 50ms delays. Not real SSE streaming.

4. MCP
The MCP module is surprisingly complete. It has multi-server support, tool namespacing, tool filtering, parallel tool execution (call_tools_parallel), reconnection logic (stdio ensure_started restarts dead processes), auth per server, manifest caching (RetryMCPClient), circuit breaker, and Docker lifecycle management.

MF-14: No MCP reconnection for SSE/HTTP clients — MEDIUM

StdioMCPClient detects dead processes and restarts them. DefaultMCPClient and SSEMCPClient have no equivalent — if the HTTP server goes down mid-session, the client doesn't attempt reconnection. RetryMCPClient retries individual calls, but doesn't reconnect the underlying transport.

MF-15: No MCP resource/prompt protocol support — LOW

The MCP spec defines resources/list, resources/read, and prompts/list in addition to tools/*. Only tools/list and tools/call are implemented.

5. RAG
The RAG module is extensive. It has: InMemoryVectorStore, ChromaStore, metadata filtering, hybrid search (BM25 + vector), re-ranking (LLM, cross-encoder, RRF), persistence (JSON file), evaluation hooks, caching, dedup, document loaders (txt/json/md/pdf), batch ingestion, and multiple embedding providers.

MF-16: PineconeStore is a stub — MEDIUM

All methods return Err(VectorStoreError::NotImplemented(...)). Pinecone is listed as a supported store but doesn't work.

MF-17: No Weaviate/Qdrant/pgvector store — LOW

The doc header says "Pinecone, Weaviate, Chroma, and local in-memory" but only Chroma and InMemory are functional. These are popular stores users would expect.

6. Observability
MF-18: Replay mode has no state snapshots — MEDIUM

ReplayMode steps through NodeTiming entries (node name + duration) but doesn't store actual state at each step. You can see "node X took 50ms" but can't inspect what the state looked like at that point. The Checkpointer has this data but isn't connected to the replay system.

MF-19: No real-time execution hooks/events — MEDIUM

There's no event emitter or callback system for monitoring graph execution in real-time. The middleware system is close, but there's no way to subscribe to events from outside the graph (e.g., a UI dashboard). No tokio::sync::broadcast channel or similar.

MF-20: No OpenTelemetry export — LOW

The observability module uses tracing crate internally but ExecutionTrace is a custom format. There's no OTLP exporter, no way to send traces to Jaeger/Datadog/etc. The tracing spans exist but aren't structured as OTel spans.

7. Ergonomics
MF-21: Two overlapping graph APIs — HIGH

There are two separate graph systems:

graph/mod.rs + runtime/mod.rs — config-driven, uses Graph<T>, Node<T>, AgentRuntime<T>
state_graph/ — programmatic builder, uses StateGraph<S>, StateGraphBuilder<S>, FunctionNode<S>
They share nothing. Different node traits, different edge types, different execution loops. A user must choose one and can't mix them. The state_graph is the LangGraph-like API but lacks features the runtime has (middleware, plugins, evaluation). The runtime has features but requires YAML config.

MF-22: No #[node] or #[handler] derive macro — MEDIUM

Defining a node requires wrapping a closure in FunctionNode::new("name", |state| { Box::pin(async move { ... }) }). A #[node] attribute macro that turns an async fn(S) -> Result<S> into a node would cut boilerplate significantly. The flowgentra-ai-macros crate was deleted.

MF-23: StateGraphBuilder requires Arc<dyn Node> for every node — MEDIUM

add_node takes Arc<dyn Node<S>>. Users must wrap every closure in Arc::new(FunctionNode::new(...)). A convenience method like add_fn("name", |s| async { ... }) would improve ergonomics significantly.

MF-24: Router functions are not async — LOW

RouterFn<S> = Box<dyn Fn(&S) -> Result<String> + Send + Sync> is sync. If routing logic needs to check an external service or do async work, it can't. LangGraph routers can be async.

8. Ecosystem Expectations
MF-25: No human-in-the-loop beyond breakpoints — MEDIUM

interrupt_before/interrupt_after stop execution with an error. There's no mechanism to inject user input and resume. LangGraph has interrupt() that pauses, collects input, and continues. The resume mechanism exists (invoke_with_id) but there's no way to inject new data into state between interrupt and resume.

MF-26: No multi-agent orchestration — MEDIUM

No supervisor pattern, no agent-to-agent communication, no shared message bus. The orchestrator_node.rs (1352 lines) exists but it's a monolithic node, not a composable multi-agent framework. LangGraph has create_react_agent that can be nested.

MF-27: No structured output / JSON mode — LOW

chat_structured adds a system prompt asking for JSON. No JSON schema enforcement, no response_format: { type: "json_object" } parameter sent to the API. OpenAI and Anthropic both support forced JSON mode.